plugin_info.global_dashboard: Here you have the summary of everything you have on Gamma.
plugin_info.project_list: Projects are a way of organizing your repositories in Gamma. Sorting and view options can be found in the options sidebar. Learn more about managing projects in the documentation.
plugin_info.subsystem_list: Gamma supports Git, SVN and Zip repositories. GitHub and Bitbucket repositories can also be integrated through one time tokens. A project can contain multiple linked repositories.
plugin_info.repository_list_opensource: Open source Gamma account supports, only open source git repositories. Please buy a commercial license if you want to integrate private GitHub, Bitbucket or SVN repositories. With commercial license, you can do token based one time integration for Bitbucket and GitHub.
plugin_info.repository_dashboard: Dashboard for all activities on a given repository.
plugin_info.repository_overview: The repository overview allows for a high-level view of all relevant information in-regards to Gamma's four ratings: Design, Metrics, Duplication and Code Quality. Hover over the timeline to see how the code base has changed over time.
plugin_info.component_list: Component list is a master list of all components.
plugin_info.change_overview: Change overview shows a summary of all changes occurring between two selected snapshots.
plugin_info.change_list: Change overview by component shows a detailed summary of all changes occurring between two selected snapshots on a component level.
plugin_info.heatmap: The Heatmap view is a unique way to understand the big picture of your source code. A Component’s (or class’) overall rating is represented by color and its size is reflected by the lines of code it contains. The Heatmap can be filtered by adjusting the 'rating scale' slider.
plugin_info.hotspot_distribution: A hotspot is a component with a rating of 0 or less. Here you can take a look at how your hotspots are distributed across different modules.
plugin_info.design_issue_details: The design issues graph shows how Gamma’s anti-patterns are distributed across your source code. Click within the graph for further navigation.
plugin_info.metrics_details: Gamma measures the code against different code metrics. Excessive code metric violations should be carefully watched. Click within the graph for further navigation.
plugin_info.coverage_component_list: View code coverage on individual components here.
plugin_info.unit_tests: View the status of all unit tests here.
plugin_info.duplication_details: The duplication distribution graph shows where code blocks are copied and pasted.
plugin_info.code_issues_details: Code issues are localized issues in code. Gamma detects hundreds of code issues. See how they are distributed across modules.
plugin_info.coverage_distribution: View code coverage distribution across modules.
plugin_info.component_explorer: Component explorer gives insight about design issues, duplication, code issues etc. in a component.
plugin_info.file_explorer: File explorer gives insight about code issues and design issues in a file.
plugin_info.dependency_plot: Click through the components (dots) to unveil the network of dependencies.
plugin_info.tasks: A Task is an actionable item that can be created against a module or component (package or class) and directly assigned to a team member.
plugin_info.issues: This is a list of all design and code issues. To see where the issue within the source code, click on the specific issue. Tasks can be created and assigned to a Gamma user directly from an issue with the 'create task' button.
plugin_info.task_list: List of all tasks present across all projects.
plugin_info.issue_list: List of all issues present across all projects.
plugin_info.partitions: When a component or class is too big and complex, it is advisable to divide it into smaller and more manageable components. Gamma algorithms show ways of how you can derive new, more manageable, components. Use the slider to adjust the granularity of the components.
plugin_info.users: This list reflects all users attached to your account. Learn more about how to add and manage users in the documentation.
plugin_info.global_permissions: Manage the administrative roles of users here. Learn more about the individual roles and their abilities in the documentation.
plugin_info.version_control: GitHub and Bitbucket account integration is supported with one time tokens. Linking an account will allow Gamma to seamlessly access your repositories and easily add or remove repositories to projects. Learn more about how to create version control account in the documentation.
plugin_info.kpis: Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) classify issues in the source code into different categories. This helps in prioritization while creating a refactoring plan. Learn more about KPIs and how to manage them in the documentation.
plugin_info.kpi_dashboard: Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) classify issues in the source code into different categories. This helps in prioritization while creating a refactoring plan. Learn more about KPIs and how to manage them in the documentation.
plugin_info.tags: Gamma users can tag components and modules to organize source code. You can create tag categories and tags for the users to choose from. Learn more about creating and managing tags in the documentation.
plugin_info.analysis_queue: All scan requests currently queued or in progress.
plugin_info.license: Your license, in real-time. Click 'Manage License' to purchase upgrades and add-ons.
plugin_info.quality_profile: Quality gates help you maintain your software by comparing it to pre-defined thresholds. Learn more about managing quality gates in the documentation
plugin_info.complex_method_list: These methods needs to be tested on priority
plugin_info.repositories: All linked repositories are displayed here. Learn more about managing repositories in the documentation.
plugin_info.access_tokens: Manage the gamma access token here

description.maintainability: Defines the consistency and coherence of the overall design. This includes the way that components or modules are designs, as well as factors such as coding style and variable naming. Analysability, changability , stability and testability are also characterized here.
description.reusability: Characterizes the development effort for a software developer to integrate a component in a new system.
description.functionality: Characterizes functional correctness of the software and the amount of functional defect.
description.runtime behaviour: Characterizes behavior of software from time and resource perspective. Characterizes frequency of failure, ability to withstand component failure, ability to recover from a failed state. Characterizes the ability to cope with unknown errors during execution or the ability of an algorithm to continue to operate despite abnormalities in input, calculations, etc
description.portability: Characterizes the amount of changes needed for the adaption of software to different specified environments. Also Characterizes the plug and play aspect of software components, that is how easy it is to exchange a given software component with a specified environment.
description.conceptualintegrity: Defines the consistency and coherence of the overall design. This includes the way that components or modules are designed, as wen as factors such as coding style and variable naming.
description.analyzability: Ability of diagnosis of deficiencies or causes of failures, or for identification of parts to be modified
description.changeability: Characterizes the amount of effort needed modification, fault removal or for environmental change
description.stability: Characterizes the risk of unexpected or negative effects as result of modfications
description.testability: Characterizes the effort needed for validating the software and about the test coverage. Good testability makes it more likely that faults in a system can be isolated in a timely and effectve manner.
description.understandability: Characterizes the amount of effort required for a new developer to understand the software components.
description.programmability: Characterizes the development effort for a software developer to integrate a component in new systems
description.accuracy: Characterizes functional correctness of the software and the amount of functonal defects
description.security: Characterizes the security vulnerabilities that exist in software components. This includes issues like clear-text password, scripting vulnerabilities, permission violations, etc.
description.efficiency: Characterizes behavior of software from time perspective (e.g. response times. throughput, etc.)
description.resourceutilization: Characterizes behavior Of software from resource perspective (i.e. memory, CPU, disk, network usage)
description.resource utilization: Characterizes behavior Of software from resource perspective (i.e. memory, CPU, disk, network usage)
description.reliability: Characterizes frequency of failure, ability to withstand component failure, ability to recover from a failed state
description.robustness: Characterizes the ablity to cope with unknown errors during execution or the ability of an algorithm to continue to operate despite abnormalities in input, calculatons, etc
description.adaptability: Characterizes the mount of changes needed for the adaptation of software to different specified*ed environments
description.replacability: Characterizes the plug and play aspect of software components, that is how easy is it to exchange a green software component within a specified environment

design_issues.GC_description: God class is a class that single-handedly implements large blocks of functionality within a system and performs multiple, non-cohesive functionalities.
design_issues.BC_description: Brain Class is a class that is complex partly because it implements a significant amount of system intelligence and partly because it holds one or more Brain methods.
design_issues.BM_description: Brain method is a method that tends to centralize the functionality of its owner class (very much in a way a God Class tends to centralize a system’s intelligence)
design_issues.GB_description: A Global Breakable is a structural anti-pattern for a system component that is often affected when any other component is changed
design_issues.GBU_description: Global Butterfly is a structural pattern for an object that has many global dependents.
design_issues.GBR_description: A Global Breakable is a structural anti-pattern for a system component that is often affected when any other component is changed.
design_issues.LB_description: Local Butterfly is a structural pattern for a component that has many immediate dependents.
design_issues.LBU_description: Local Butterfly is a structural pattern for a component that has many immediate dependents.
design_issues.LBR_description: A Local Breakable is a component that depends on too many other components.It is likely to get impacted when any of it's direct dependencies change.
design_issues.GH_description: A Global Hub is a component that has both, a high number of global dependents and is also globally dependent on too many components.
design_issues.IC_description: When methods of a class excessively access operations of one or a few other classes, it is said that the class is intensively coupled with those one or few provider classes.
design_issues.DC_description: Data classes are “dumb” data holders without complex functionality.
design_issues.SS_description: Responsibility of the module is spread across many files.
design_issues.TH_description: The Feature Envy anti-pattern is one where a method seems more interested in a class other than the one it actually is in.
design_issues.FE_description: Struct/ classes declared in header expose the internals. They should be moved to .c/ .cpp source files.
design_issues.FI_description: Large interface with many exposed methods/ functions.
design_issues.FIC_description: Large interface with many exposed methods/ functions.
design_issues.FME_description: Struct/ classes declared in header expose the internals. They should be moved to .c/ .cpp source files.
design_issues.SSP_description: Responsibility of the module is spread across many files.
design_issues.DCL_description: Methods/ functions which are not called by external modules/ components should not be exposed.
design_issues.DE_description: Variables should not be exposed in the header files.
design_issues.MC_description: Long sequence of outgoing method/ function calls detected.
design_issues.UM_description: Methods/ functions which are not called should be considered for removal.
